  "prompt": "How do emergency rooms treat panic attacks?",
  "response": "Emergency rooms typically approach panic attacks with the following steps:\n\n1. Initial Assessment\n- Vital signs check\n- Medical history review\n- Physical examination\n- Rule out other medical conditions with similar symptoms\n\n2. Immediate Interventions\n- Provide a calm, quiet environment\n- Offer reassurance and emotional support\n- Help patient practice deep breathing techniques\n- Monitor for potential cardiac or respiratory issues\n\n3. Medical Treatment\n- Oxygen, if needed\n- Intravenous fluids for hydration\n- Possible administration of anti-anxiety medications like:\n- Benzodiazepines (e.g., Ativan, Xanax)\n- Short-acting anti-anxiety medications\n\n4. Diagnostic Tests (if necessary)\n- EKG to check heart function\n- Blood tests\n- Chest X-ray\n- To rule out other potential medical conditions\n\n5. Follow-up Recommendations\n- Referral to mental health professional\n- Suggestions for ongoing anxiety management\n- Potential prescription for anxiety medication\n- Recommendation for therapy or counseling\n\n6. Discharge\n- Provide instructions for managing future panic attacks\n- Offer resources for mental health support\n\nThe primary goal is to ensure patient safety and provide immediate symptom relief.",
